parameters.command:
=bash -lc '
set -Eeuo pipefail

# ===== Inputs =====
ARG_IN="${1:-}"
FILENAME="{{ $('Read/Write Files from Disk').item.json.fileName || '' }}"

# ===== Config =====
W="${W:-1280}"
H="${H:-720}"
MAX_KB="${MAX_KB:-2000}"       # 2MB
MODE="${MODE:-stretch}"        # stretch | cover | pad
BG="${BG:-#000000}"
FORCE_SAME_PATH="${FORCE_SAME_PATH:-0}"  # 0 = gera .jpg; 1 = sobrescreve mesmo caminho (cuidado com MIME)

# ===== Resolve caminho de entrada =====
if [ -n "${ARG_IN:-}" ]; then
  IN="$ARG_IN"
else
  IN="$FILENAME"
fi

[ -n "${IN:-}" ] || { echo "Erro: não recebi caminho de entrada (nem \$1, nem fileName)."; exit 2; }
[ -e "$IN" ] || { echo "Erro: caminho não existe: $IN"; exit 2; }

# ===== ImageMagick =====
IM="$(command -v magick || true)"
if [ -z "$IM" ]; then IM="$(command -v convert || true)"; fi
[ -z "$IM" ] && { echo "ImageMagick não encontrado (magick/convert)"; exit 1; }

dir="$(dirname "$IN")"
base="$(basename "$IN")"
name="${base%.*}"

tmp="$(mktemp -p "$dir" ytfix_XXXXXXXX).jpg"

# ===== Redimensionamento =====
case "$MODE" in
  stretch)
    resize_args=( -resize "${W}x${H}!" )
    ;;
  pad)
    resize_args=( -resize "${W}x${H}" -background "$BG" -gravity center -extent "${W}x${H}" )
    ;;
  cover|*)
    resize_args=( -resize "${W}x${H}^" -gravity center -extent "${W}x${H}" )
    ;;
esac

# 1ª tentativa: limitar por tamanho com jpeg:extent
if [ "$(basename "$IM")" = "magick" ]; then
  "$IM" "$IN[0]" -auto-orient "${resize_args[@]}" \
    -strip -sampling-factor 4:2:0 -interlace JPEG -colorspace sRGB \
    -define "jpeg:extent=${MAX_KB}kb" "$tmp" 2>/dev/null || true
else
  "$IM" "$IN" -auto-orient "${resize_args[@]}" \
    -strip -sampling-factor 4:2:0 -interlace JPEG -colorspace sRGB \
    -define "jpeg:extent=${MAX_KB}kb" "$tmp" 2>/dev/null || true
fi

size() { wc -c < "$1" | tr -d " "; }

# Fallback: iterar qualidade se ainda passou do limite
if [ ! -s "$tmp" ] || [ "$(size "$tmp")" -gt $(( MAX_KB * 1024 )) ]; then
  for q in 85 80 75 70 65 60 55 50 45 40; do
    if [ "$(basename "$IM")" = "magick" ]; then
      "$IM" "$IN[0]" -auto-orient "${resize_args[@]}" \
        -strip -sampling-factor 4:2:0 -interlace JPEG -colorspace sRGB \
        -quality "$q" "$tmp"
    else
      "$IM" "$IN" -auto-orient "${resize_args[@]}" \
        -strip -sampling-factor 4:2:0 -interlace JPEG -colorspace sRGB \
        -quality "$q" "$tmp"
    fi
    [ "$(size "$tmp")" -le $(( MAX_KB * 1024 )) ] && break
  done
fi

# ===== Saída =====
if [ "$FORCE_SAME_PATH" = "1" ]; then
  # sobrescreve exatamente o mesmo caminho (atenção à extensão)
  cp -f -- "$tmp" "$IN"
  rm -f -- "$tmp"
  OUT="$IN"
else
  OUT="$dir/$name.jpg"
  rm -f -- "$IN"
  mv -f -- "$tmp" "$OUT"
fi

printf "{\"path\":\"%s\",\"bytes\":%s}\n" "$OUT" "$(size "$OUT")"
' -- "{{ $json.path || '' }}"

json.output_VideoDescription: Practice your English shadowing by listening first, then repeating, and finally shadowing along with the narrative. This video focuses on first and second conditionals to help you understand how different choices can affect outcomes. In this story, Evan wakes up hopeful but uncertain, reflecting on how his decisions—like catching a certain train—impact his destiny. Through his encounters and reflections, you'll hear conditionals like "if you wait," "if things go wrong," and "if I had taken the other train." This engaging narrative uses everyday language to help you practice conditionals naturally and encourages you to think about possibilities and consequences. You'll also notice key phrasal verbs and expressions that keep the story lively and relatable. Listen once, then repeat aloud, then shadow with the audio to improve your fluency and confidence in using conditionals in conversation.
json.output:
Evan woke early on a cold morning with a heart full of hope and doubt He prepared for his journey as he studied the schedule and counted the minutes and if he caught the next train he knew that his life might change It was clear that if I had taken the other train I would never have met her a truth that lingered in his mind and he felt a mixture of fear and excitement and knew that every decision paved the way for a new destiny

On the platform Evan met a stranger who offered advice and a smile The man said that if you wait for a sign you might find your true path and that if things go wrong you can always try again Evan listened with caution and wondered if he were brave enough to risk the unknown in a world full of many chances and hidden opportunities

Evan embarked on his journey with a mind full of questions and his heart open for the future He remembered that if he would wait patiently the time would bring a new beginning and he also thought that if he took every step with careful thought he could master the challenges ahead and transform each risk into a valuable lesson for his life

On a bright afternoon the train station buzzed with life and plans Evan saw a familiar face in a crowd and he recalled his words that if he looked for a friend he would surely find support The day felt charged with a promise and if he engaged with the people around him he might uncover hidden dreams and new directions that had long been waiting to emerge

That evening Evan found himself lost in thought under a sky full of soft light He mused that if he could rewrite the moments he would choose courage over fear and if fate allowed him a second chance he would always embrace the unknown His mind danced with visions of a future filled with love and hope on paths that lay undiscovered

In the quiet of the night Evan recalled a lesson that he had learned from the chance encounter and he felt a warmth in his heart If he dared to dream he could create a world of wonder and if he continued to trust his feelings the truth would shine brightly in each new step of his journey as he moved forward with resolve
json.output_VideoTitle: Level B2 | English Shadowing Narrative Using First and Second Conditionals
